{{Use Australian English|date=May 2017}}
'''John Vincent Stanley Megaw''' (born 1934)<ref name="Antiquity">[https://www.academia.edu/1827385/Megaw_ant0860546 The Flying Dutchman reaches port Vincent Megaw  ''Antiquity'' 86 (2012): 546–557]</ref><ref name="Springer">[https://link.springer.com/referenceworkentry/10.1007%2F978-1-4419-0465-2_2392 Encyclopedia of Global Archaeology - Megaw, Vincent], [[Springer Science+Business Media]], pp 4769-4772, 2014, {{DOI|10.1007/978-1-4419-0465-2_2392}}, Subscription required for full article</ref> is a British-born Australian archaeologist with research interests focusing on the archaeology and anthropology of art and musical instruments, Australasian prehistory and protohistory. He is a specialist in early [[Celtic art]] and contemporary Australian Indigenous art.<ref>[http://www.eoas.info/biogs/P002021b.htm Encyclopedia of Australian Science 2010]</ref>

Megaw was educated at University College School, Hampstead and the [[University of Edinburgh]], and worked on a number key sites in Europe as well as carrying out pioneering work in the South Sydney region of Australia. He undertook extensive research with his wife, '''Ruth Megaw''', on the art of the European pre-Roman [[Iron Age]]; they wrote several publications together. In 1961, after working as an editor at Thames and Hudson, he accepted a position at the [[University of Sydney]] as Lecturer and subsequently Senior Lecturer in European Iron Age Archaeology. From 1971 to 1982 he held the Chair of Archaeology and Head of Department at Leicester University.  His other appointments have included Visiting Professorship at the [[University of Edinburgh]] and Senior Honorary Research Fellow in the Department of Archaeology at the [[University of Glasgow]] (from 1998 with his wife).<ref name="Antiquity"/> Ruth Megaw died in 2013.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/education/2013/jul/30/ruth-megaw Ruth Megaw obituary by Vincent Megaw, ''The Guardian'' Wednesday 31 July 2013]</ref>

He was elected to the [[Australian Academy of the Humanities]] in 1985 and in 2004 was made a Member of the Order of Australia.<ref>[http://www.humanities.org.au/Fellowship/FindFellows/tabid/123/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/1245/Megaw-Vincent.aspx The Academy Fellows] [[Australian Academy of the Humanities]]</ref>

==Select publications==
*Megaw, Ruth and Vincent, ''Celtic Art'', 1989, Thames and Hudson, {{ISBN|0500050503}}

